xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree

Class PrimitiveType

  • java.lang.Object
    • xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree.ManagedType
      • xxl.core.indexStructures.builder.BPlusTree.PrimitiveType

  • public class PrimitiveType
extends ManagedType
    Use this class if the index structure should use standard java objects.

    Examples By the following a BPlusTree for using float objects is created. After data importing, a range query is executed. 
     BPlusTreeConfiguration requirements = new BPlusTreeConfiguration(new PrimitiveType(JavaType.FLOAT, "FloatTable"));
 myTree = requirements.getBuilder().create();
 for(float i = 0; i < 100_000; i++)
    myTree.insert(i);
    
 Cursor c = myTree.rangeQuery(new Float(20_000), new Float(20_020));
 Cursors.println(c);
    See Also:
    Use tuples for an index structure, How to setup a BPlus tree easy and fast

      • getContentClass

        public ManagedType.ContentClass getContentClass()
        Description copied from class: ManagedType
        Returns the current ContentClass which indicates the managed data type for this index structure This Class determines the index managed type class. This could be primitive data types (CONTENT_CLASS_PRIMITIVE) or complex (tuple) data types (CONTENT_CLASS_COMPLEX). To get information about which type is actually manages, call ManagedType.getContentClassSubType() .
        Specified by:

      • getContentType

        public String getContentType()
        Description copied from class: ManagedType
        When storing an index structure to hard drive on top of the content the meta data will be written. This meta data contains a (unique) ContentType string which identifies the managed data. If the index structure manages e.g. tuples, "complex/tuples" could the identifier. This is used to check the configuration when restoring an index structure from persistent storage.
        Specified by:
        getContentType in class ManagedType
        Returns:
        Unique identifier for the managed content
